            <notesStmt>
                <note type="summary">
                    
                        
                            <p>A letter from Gladys Johnson to Ellen Vickery, written on May 15th 1916. Gladys Ruth Johnson (b.1890) was training to be a nurse at the Adelaide Hospital in Dublin at the time of the Easter Rising in 1916.  The hospital in Peter Street was close to the fighting and she writes about how the patients were moved to the cellars to keep them safe from the bullets. She writes how Jacobs Factory was occupied by 'Sinn Feinners' and they were give five chances to surrender because if the building had been blown up it would have meant damaging the hospital.</p>
                        
                            <p> Gladys qualified as a nurse later in the year and then volunteered to work as a VAD in France nursing the troops.  She joined the Queen Alexandra's Medical Corps.  Her fianc√©e , Dr Percy Vickery, was in the Royal Medical Corps and was stationed in Egypt, Gallipoli and Palestine.  They married in June 1918 and subsequently moved to England and settled in Hampshire where Percy was a GP.</p>
                        
                    
                </note>
