<opener><address><addrLine>Adelaide</addrLine></address> <dateline><date>15.5.16</date></dateline> <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Vickery</salute></opener> <p>I think it is quite time I sent you <lb/> a few lines, and you are perhaps wondering <lb/> when you are going to hear.</p> <p>I have been hearing about you all from <lb/> Alice.  I am sure you were all delighted <lb/> to have her with you for Easter, and for longer <lb/> than you expected &#x2014; What terrible times <lb/>we have had!  it makes one wonder <lb/>what we will hear next, and we little dreamt <lb/> of rebellion in Dublin -&#x2014; Things have <lb/> quietened down wonderfully well, but occasionally <lb/> still odd shots are to be heard, &amp; only 2 <lb/> nights ago a soldier was shot down &amp; bought <lb/> to Mercer's hospital.  Being so near to  <lb/> Jacobs, we felt rather nervous, it was occupied <lb/> all week by the Sinn <sic>Feinners</sic>, and we seemed <lb/> to live amid the whirl &amp; buzz of flying bullets. <lb/> it seemed quite like a week at the "Front" &amp; <lb/> made us realize what it must all be like, but <lb/> one week was quite enough &amp; we were thankful
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="2179" facs="#L1916_861_img_2179"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>when it was all over, and with no serious <lb/>damage except broken window panes &#x2014;  <lb/> the poor patients were terrified, they were all <lb/> put down in the cellars on mattresses, &amp; we <lb/> ourselves had to sleep on the corridors two <lb/> on a mattress.  The bedrooms were not safe <lb/> with the bullets flying in, and some of the nurses <lb/> had narrow escapes.  The <addrLine>Adelaide</addrLine> certainly <lb/> saved Jacobs from being blown up.  They got 5 <lb/> chances to surrender on account of us, as it <lb/> would have meant damage to the hospital as well. <lb/> Sackville St is one mass of ruin <lb/> &#x2014; <p>I was sorry to hear that Sam was so near to  <lb/> you &amp; you didn't see him, it must have been <lb/> very tantalizing, but perhaps he may come <lb/> round that way soon again.</p>  <p>Percy seems to keep well and happy, &amp; it is <lb/> nice to hear where he really is at last &#x2014; I am  <lb/> wondering when he will get 'leave', he is 6 <lb/> months out this month, but of course from <lb/> Egypt they don't get leave so often - he says <lb/> he feels much better out there than in this  <lb/> climate, so that is a good thing -  I suppose <lb/> he will be Khaki colour when he gets back!</p> <closer><salute>Much love to each one of you -  Lovingly</salute> <signed><hi rend="underline">Gladys</hi></signed></closer>
        
    
         
        <pb n="2180" facs="#L1916_861_img_2180"/>
        
        
           
            Photograph of Gladys Johnson, nurse with child
        
    
